{"ts":"2026-06-27T21:48:04.242Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_end","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Initiating S3 Integration**\n\nI've confirmed `boto3` and `python-multipart` are installed. Now, I'm focusing on crafting file upload and download endpoints. To clarify, I'm now exploring standard S3 file upload using Python to establish a solid foundation for the implementation.\n\n\n**Addressing Credential Handling**\n\nI'm now grappling with credential management for S3 integration. I realized that without proper AWS credentials, `boto3` can throw errors. My focus is on simulating S3 in the absence of credentials, drawing inspiration from the DynamoDB mock. My design includes a mock S3 client that defaults to local file storage if real `boto3` fails or if we are not in production or any AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID variable is missing. This ensures robust local development.\n\n\n**Defining Local S3 Structure**\n\nI've decided on a local storage structure, now. I will use a local directory to simulate S3. I'll store files under `backend/local_s3_storage`, mirroring the real S3 structure for local testing. Specifically, I will follow clients/<client_id>/documents/<document_id>/<filename> as a model for local file paths. Now, I am focused on verifying endpoint requirements and I am planning on working on the `backend/app/api/routes/documents.py` file. I am looking at the Next.js routes under `app/api/v1/documents/route.ts` and `[id]/route.ts` to guide this.\n\n\n**Clarifying Backend Scope**\n\nI'm now clarifying the scope of \"backend.\" I am trying to figure out if it refers to the Python backend, the Next.js backend, or both. Since the request mentions both, I'm analyzing the design to determine the intended architecture. Specifically, I'm examining the connection between the portal/admin UI and the backends to see if both APIs are aligned, or if the portal/admin UI hits only Next.js. I'm focusing on the interaction to determine how to proceed with the S3 implementation.\n\n\n"}}
