{"ts":"2026-06-27T21:48:38.451Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_end","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Defining the Upload Route**\n\nOkay, I've got a clear plan now. For handling documents, I need to make a `documents.py` file in the route directory. This file will define the `/upload` endpoint. Administrators can use this to upload files to S3. I will also save associated metadata in GFF_. This seems fairly straightforward.\n\n\n**Refining the Upload Endpoint**\n\nI'm now zeroing in on the upload endpoint design. I've decided it will accept `file: UploadFile` along with other parameters like `client_id`, `project_id`, and metadata via a FastAPI `Form`. I want to ensure it's clean and flexible with default values. Metadata will be stored as DOCUMENT records in `GFF_PORTAL_ITEMS`, and files will go to S3 under `clients/<client_id>/documents/<document_id>/<filename>`. I'm starting to think about how to structure the data for storage.\n\n\n**Analyzing Document Structures**\n\nI'm now comparing the TypeScript structure for a `DOCUMENT` record with its Python counterparts. My aim is to ensure consistency. I'm focusing on the fields, especially the type, size, and metadata. I'm also ensuring the field naming conventions align across both implementations. Specifically, I'm examining how fields like `id`, `title`, and `version` are handled.\n\n\n**Defining Python Data Models**\n\nI'm now delving into the Python data models, particularly for the `DOCUMENT` record, to ensure it interfaces with `GFF_PORTAL_ITEMS`. I'm confirming that `client_id`, `project_id`, `title`, and more, are accurately reflected. I'm noting the `portal_items_repo` reads/writes to `settings.DYNAMODB_ITEMS_TABLE`. Let's ensure `documents.py` in python uses `portal_items_repo` to manage DOCUMENT metadata. I am also working on endpoints. I have these ideas:\n`POST /api/v1/documents/upload` - upload.\n`GET /api/v1/documents` - list.\n`GET /api/v1/documents/{id}/download` - download.\n\n\n**Implementing Access Control**\n\nI'm now integrating access controls for the document endpoints. The recent focus has been ensuring that client users can only access documents associated with their `client_id`. I'm going to implement role-based access checks in the list and download endpoints.\n\nI've also thought about how files are uploaded to S3. Now, I'm defining an S3 storage manager in `backend/app/services/s3_storage.py`. This manager will use `boto3` for real S3 operations and fall back to local file storage when running in a mock mode, for easier testing. I want to check for potential initialization failures with `boto3`.\n\n\n**Verifying S3 Connection**\n\nI'm now implementing the `S3StorageManager`. It starts with a default to mock mode. Then, it attempts real S3 initialization using `boto3`. I've added a check to see if AWS credentials are set and if they are \"local\". If initialization fails, or if we are in local development, it will log the issue, and revert to mock storage, and if it works, it lists buckets to verify the connection.\n\n\n**Confirming S3 File Upload**\n\nI've tested the S3 upload functionality in the `S3StorageManager`. It successfully handles both real S3 uploads using `boto3` and the fallback mock storage on local disk. This covers the upload path with detailed logging on different storage scenarios, including credential and initialization tests, and mock directory management.\n\n\n**Testing Download Functionality**\n\nI'm now writing the download file function for the S3 storage manager. I am using `boto3` to fetch files from S3 when not in mock mode. I'll test how to handle files and return the content as bytes. I'll also add mock behavior for local file retrieval in the mock mode. Error handling and logging are key priorities.\n\n\n"}}
