{"ts":"2026-06-27T21:49:57.186Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Designing the API Router**\n\nI'm making good headway designing the `backend/app/api/routes/documents.py` router. The plan includes a secure, multipart document upload via `POST /upload`. It will take a `UploadFile` and require thoughtful validation, which will include authorization and input cleaning before storage. I am now exploring security considerations around file uploads.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-27T21:49:58.219Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Refining Input Validation**\n\nI've refined the input validation for the document upload route. I now handle authorization by checking the user's role and client ID. Admins and GFF Admins have unrestricted upload access. Client users can only upload to their own client, enforced by checking `current_user.client_id` against the submitted `client_id`. This also takes into account optional fields.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-27T21:50:00.369Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Implementing Document ID Generation**\n\nI've decided to leverage `portal_items_repo._get_next_id(\"DOCUMENT\")` for thread-safe and consistent `document_id` generation, ensuring it aligns with our existing system. I'm now implementing the S3 upload using the generated ID.\n\nI'm calculating the `sha256` hash, formatting the file size, and inserting a `DOCUMENT` record into `GFF_PORTAL_ITEMS` via the `portal_items_repo`. After considering the implications, I'll also insert a new `DocumentItem` into the SQLite database, mirroring existing route handler interactions.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
